WEBVTT

00:00:01.097 --> 00:00:02.841
Part two of Culture and
Team, and

00:00:02.841 --> 00:00:05.708
we have Ben Silverman, the
founder of Pinterest, and

00:00:05.708 --> 00:00:08.530
John and Patrick Collison,
the founders of Stripe.

00:00:10.510 --> 00:00:13.300
Founders that have obviously
sort of, some of the best in

00:00:13.300 --> 00:00:15.190
the world at thinking about
culture and

00:00:15.190 --> 00:00:15.940
how they build teams.

00:00:15.940 --> 00:00:18.400
So, there&#39;s three areas that
we&#39;re gonna cover today.

00:00:18.400 --> 00:00:20.690
One will just be sort of
general thoughts on

00:00:20.690 --> 00:00:22.980
culture as a follow up to
the last lecture.

00:00:22.980 --> 00:00:25.580
And then we&#39;re really gonna
dig into what happens at

00:00:25.580 --> 00:00:27.120
the founding of these
companies.

00:00:27.120 --> 00:00:28.790
And building out the early
team.

00:00:28.790 --> 00:00:32.530
And then how that changes
and evolves as these

00:00:32.530 --> 00:00:35.940
guys have scaled their
companies up to 100 plus.

00:00:35.940 --> 00:00:37.270
I don&#39;t even know how many
people you have now,

00:00:37.270 --> 00:00:38.380
but quite a lot.

00:00:38.380 --> 00:00:39.520
Very large organizations and

00:00:39.520 --> 00:00:41.240
how you adapt these
principles of culture.

00:00:42.910 --> 00:00:46.205
But to start off I just
wanna ask a very

00:00:46.205 --> 00:00:47.970
open-ended question which
is,

00:00:47.970 --> 00:00:51.010
what are the core pieces of
culture that you found to

00:00:51.010 --> 00:00:52.951
be most important in
building out your companies?

00:00:52.951 --> 00:00:56.720
&gt;&gt; So what are the most
important parts?

00:00:58.130 --> 00:01:01.829
&gt;&gt; It&#39;s on.
&gt;&gt; Oh, it&#39;s on.

00:01:01.829 --> 00:01:02.769
Yeah I mean I think for

00:01:02.769 --> 00:01:04.910
us, like we think about on a
few dimensions.

00:01:04.910 --> 00:01:05.780
One is like who do we hire,

00:01:05.780 --> 00:01:07.180
and what do those people
value?

00:01:08.710 --> 00:01:11.950
Two is what do we do every
day, like why do we do it?

00:01:13.180 --> 00:01:15.460
Three is what do we choose
to communicate?

00:01:15.460 --> 00:01:17.480
And then I think the fourth
is what we

00:01:17.480 --> 00:01:18.460
choose to celebrate.

00:01:18.460 --> 00:01:19.220
I guess the converse of

00:01:19.220 --> 00:01:20.590
that is like what you choose
to punish.

00:01:20.590 --> 00:01:23.880
But in general I think
running a company based on

00:01:23.880 --> 00:01:24.490
what you celebrate,

00:01:24.490 --> 00:01:26.360
is more exciting than what
you punish.

00:01:26.360 --> 00:01:29.040
But I think those four
things kind of make up

00:01:29.040 --> 00:01:30.040
the bulk of it for us.

00:01:35.796 --> 00:01:38.666
&gt;&gt; We&#39;ve placed a large
emphasis on, as Stripe has

00:01:38.666 --> 00:01:41.536
grown and probably more than
other companies is,

00:01:41.536 --> 00:01:43.560
transparency internally.

00:01:43.560 --> 00:01:44.940
And I think it&#39;s been
something that&#39;s been

00:01:44.940 --> 00:01:45.505
really valuable for

00:01:45.505 --> 00:01:48.460
Stripe, and also a little
bit misunderstood.

00:01:49.590 --> 00:01:53.740
All the things people talk
about like hiring really

00:01:53.740 --> 00:01:57.070
great people, or giving them
a huge amount of leverage.

00:01:57.070 --> 00:02:00.220
Transparency for us plays
into that.

00:02:00.220 --> 00:02:03.335
We think that, if you are
aligned at a high

00:02:03.335 --> 00:02:07.340
level about what Stripe is
doing, if everyone really

00:02:07.340 --> 00:02:11.078
believes in the mission, and
then if everyone has

00:02:11.078 --> 00:02:14.639
really good access to
information, and kind of

00:02:14.639 --> 00:02:18.401
has a good picture of the
current state of Stripe.

00:02:18.401 --> 00:02:21.175
Then that gets you a huge
amount of the way there in

00:02:21.175 --> 00:02:24.230
terms of working
productively together.

00:02:24.230 --> 00:02:26.760
And it kind of forgives a
lot of the other things that

00:02:26.760 --> 00:02:29.790
tend to break as you, as you
grow a start-up.

00:02:29.790 --> 00:02:33.090
As we&#39;ve grown, we started
off two people.

00:02:33.090 --> 00:02:33.980
We&#39;re now over 170 people.

00:02:33.980 --> 00:02:37.160
We&#39;ve put a lot of thought
into the tooling that

00:02:37.160 --> 00:02:41.170
goes around transparency,
because at 170 people,

00:02:41.170 --> 00:02:44.100
there is so much information
being produced,

00:02:44.100 --> 00:02:46.420
that you can&#39;t just consume
it all as a fire hose.

00:02:46.420 --> 00:02:47.300
And so

00:02:47.300 --> 00:02:49.820
how we use slack, how we use
email, things like that.

00:02:49.820 --> 00:02:51.030
We can go into it more
later.

00:02:51.030 --> 00:02:52.420
But I think that&#39;s one of

00:02:52.420 --> 00:02:54.060
the core things that&#39;s
helped us work well.

00:02:55.300 --> 00:02:58.180
&gt;&gt; I think culture to some
degree is basically kind of

00:02:58.180 --> 00:03:00.790
the resolution to a
bandwidth problem.

00:03:00.790 --> 00:03:04.480
In the sense that, maybe
when you start out working

00:03:04.480 --> 00:03:06.270
on something, you&#39;re sort of
coding all the time, but you

00:03:06.270 --> 00:03:08.580
can&#39;t code all the things
that you think the product

00:03:08.580 --> 00:03:10.440
might need, or the company
might need, or whatever, and

00:03:10.440 --> 00:03:13.150
you so you decide to work
with more coders, right?

00:03:15.420 --> 00:03:17.870
And so the organization gets
larger.

00:03:17.870 --> 00:03:19.590
And maybe, in some idealized
world,

00:03:19.590 --> 00:03:21.750
I don&#39;t think this actually
true, but kind of ideally

00:03:21.750 --> 00:03:23.950
you could be involved in
every single decision, and

00:03:23.950 --> 00:03:26.370
every single sort of moment
of the company, and

00:03:26.370 --> 00:03:28.820
everything that happens, but
obviously you can&#39;t, or

00:03:28.820 --> 00:03:30.260
maybe you can if two people.

00:03:30.260 --> 00:03:32.440
But you certainly can&#39;t at
even like five or

00:03:32.440 --> 00:03:34.530
ten kind of that point comes
very quickly,

00:03:34.530 --> 00:03:36.710
then by the time you&#39;re 50
it&#39;s completely hopeless.

00:03:36.710 --> 00:03:39.570
And so culture is kind of
how you kind of,

00:03:39.570 --> 00:03:44.110
what the strands are that
you sort of want to have,

00:03:44.110 --> 00:03:46.630
the invariance that you want
to kind of maintain,

00:03:47.670 --> 00:03:50.840
as you can get specifically
involved in sort of

00:03:50.840 --> 00:03:53.338
fewer and fewer decisions
over time.

00:03:53.338 --> 00:03:56.192
And I think when you think
about it that way it,

00:03:56.192 --> 00:03:59.680
maybe its kind of importance
becomes sort of

00:03:59.680 --> 00:04:00.610
self evident, right?

00:04:00.610 --> 00:04:03.030
Because again, like the
fraction of things you

00:04:03.030 --> 00:04:07.240
can be involved in directly
is diminishing, I mean,

00:04:07.240 --> 00:04:08.130
almost exponentially,

00:04:08.130 --> 00:04:10.430
sort of assuming your head
count growth sort of is

00:04:10.430 --> 00:04:14.290
on a curve that looks like
one of the great companies.

00:04:14.290 --> 00:04:17.700
And yeah that&#39;s super
important.

00:04:17.700 --> 00:04:20.648
And again, it manifests
itself in a bunch of

00:04:20.648 --> 00:04:21.850
different ways.

00:04:21.850 --> 00:04:25.680
Like for example, in hiring,
I think a large part of

00:04:25.680 --> 00:04:28.810
the reason why maybe the
first ten people you hire,

00:04:28.810 --> 00:04:29.920
what kind of goes to ship,

00:04:29.920 --> 00:04:32.760
decisions are so important
is because you&#39;re not just

00:04:32.760 --> 00:04:34.320
hiring those first ten
people.

00:04:34.320 --> 00:04:36.330
You&#39;re actually kind of
hiring 100 people.

00:04:36.330 --> 00:04:37.700
Because you should think of
kind of

00:04:37.700 --> 00:04:39.790
each one of those people as
bringing along sort of

00:04:39.790 --> 00:04:41.580
another ten people with
them, and

00:04:41.580 --> 00:04:45.830
sort of figuring out exactly
what 90 people, you would

00:04:45.830 --> 00:04:48.070
like those first ten people
to bring along is obviously

00:04:49.340 --> 00:04:53.360
gonna be quite consequential
for your company.

00:04:53.360 --> 00:04:55.940
But really briefly I think
it&#39;s largely about sort of

00:04:57.520 --> 00:04:58.020
abstraction.

00:04:59.280 --> 00:05:00.780
&gt;&gt; So one thing that a lot
of speakers in this

00:05:00.780 --> 00:05:03.910
class have touched on is how
hiring those first ten

00:05:03.910 --> 00:05:05.670
employees, if you don&#39;t get
that right,

00:05:05.670 --> 00:05:07.978
the company basically will
never recover but

00:05:07.978 --> 00:05:10.180
no one has talked about how
to do that so.

00:05:11.180 --> 00:05:14.000
What have the three of you
looked for

00:05:15.010 --> 00:05:17.190
when you&#39;ve hired these
initial employees,

00:05:17.190 --> 00:05:19.800
to get the culture of the
company right?

00:05:19.800 --> 00:05:20.835
How, how have you found
them, and

00:05:20.835 --> 00:05:21.630
what have you looked for?

00:05:24.080 --> 00:05:24.610
&gt;&gt; Sure.
So,

00:05:24.610 --> 00:05:28.542
I guess this answer is
different for every

00:05:28.542 --> 00:05:32.640
company and I&#39;ll say for us
it was very inductive.

00:05:32.640 --> 00:05:35.390
So I literally looked for
people that I wanted to work

00:05:35.390 --> 00:05:36.960
with and that I thought were
talented.

00:05:38.230 --> 00:05:39.960
I think, I&#39;ve read all these
books about culture,

00:05:39.960 --> 00:05:41.130
because when I don&#39;t know
how to do something,

00:05:41.130 --> 00:05:42.730
I first go read things and

00:05:42.730 --> 00:05:43.920
everyone has all these
frameworks.

00:05:43.920 --> 00:05:47.090
And I think one bit, big
misconception that someone

00:05:47.090 --> 00:05:49.270
said once is that people
think culture is like

00:05:49.270 --> 00:05:51.480
architecture when it&#39;s a lot
more like gardening.

00:05:51.480 --> 00:05:52.650
You know, you plant some
seeds and

00:05:52.650 --> 00:05:54.050
then you pull out weeds that
aren&#39;t working,

00:05:54.050 --> 00:05:55.570
and they sort of expand.

00:05:55.570 --> 00:05:58.650
So, when we first hired
people we hired people that

00:05:58.650 --> 00:05:59.520
were like ourselves.

00:06:01.060 --> 00:06:02.030
I often looked at like three
or

00:06:02.030 --> 00:06:04.460
four different things that I
really valued in people.

00:06:04.460 --> 00:06:06.700
You know, I looked for
people that worked hard and

00:06:06.700 --> 00:06:08.890
seemed high integrity and
low ego.

00:06:08.890 --> 00:06:10.490
I looked for people that
were creative, and

00:06:10.490 --> 00:06:12.170
I usually meant that they
were really curious.

00:06:12.170 --> 00:06:14.430
They had all these different
interests.

00:06:14.430 --> 00:06:17.120
Some of our first employees
are probably some of

00:06:17.120 --> 00:06:19.280
the quirkiest people I&#39;ve
ever met.

00:06:19.280 --> 00:06:20.250
They were engineers but

00:06:20.250 --> 00:06:22.540
they also have all these
crazy hobbies.

00:06:22.540 --> 00:06:24.390
Like one guy made his own
board game

00:06:24.390 --> 00:06:26.240
with this elaborate set of
rules.

00:06:26.240 --> 00:06:28.240
Another guy was really into
magic tricks.

00:06:28.240 --> 00:06:31.210
And he had coded not only
like this magic trick on

00:06:31.210 --> 00:06:32.000
the iPhone, but

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:35.290
he had shot the production
video with a preview.

00:06:35.290 --> 00:06:37.400
And I think that, that
quirkiness has actually been

00:06:37.400 --> 00:06:38.390
a little bit of a calling
card.

00:06:38.390 --> 00:06:40.770
And we find that really
creative, quirky people that

00:06:40.770 --> 00:06:42.710
are excited about many
disciplines, and are

00:06:42.710 --> 00:06:46.720
extraordinary at one tend to
build really great products.

00:06:46.720 --> 00:06:49.220
They tend to be great at
collaborating.

00:06:49.220 --> 00:06:50.610
Then the last thing is, we
really look for

00:06:50.610 --> 00:06:51.390
people that wanted to,

00:06:51.390 --> 00:06:54.180
they just wanted to build
something great, and

00:06:54.180 --> 00:06:56.720
they weren&#39;t arrogant about
it, but they just felt like,

00:06:56.720 --> 00:06:58.190
it&#39;d be really cool to take
a risk and

00:06:58.190 --> 00:07:00.530
build something bigger than
themselves.

00:07:01.670 --> 00:07:02.790
And that, in the beginning,
is very,

00:07:02.790 --> 00:07:05.250
very easy to select for if
you&#39;re in our situation.

00:07:05.250 --> 00:07:08.260
We had this horrible office,
like, nobody got paid.

00:07:08.260 --> 00:07:10.530
So there was no external
reason, other than being

00:07:10.530 --> 00:07:12.810
excited about building
something to join.

00:07:12.810 --> 00:07:14.770
In fact, there was every
reason not to.

00:07:14.770 --> 00:07:16.410
And that&#39;s something,
looking back,

00:07:16.410 --> 00:07:17.170
I really, really value,

00:07:17.170 --> 00:07:19.080
because we always knew
people were joining for

00:07:19.080 --> 00:07:20.275
the purest reasons, and in
fact,

00:07:20.275 --> 00:07:23.680
were willing to forgo other
great job opportunities,

00:07:23.680 --> 00:07:27.190
market salary, a clean
office,

00:07:27.190 --> 00:07:29.540
good equipment just for the
chance to work.

00:07:29.540 --> 00:07:32.540
So, to this day I think a
lot of those traits have

00:07:32.540 --> 00:07:33.230
been seeded and

00:07:33.230 --> 00:07:35.050
are embedded in the folks
that we look at now.

00:07:37.990 --> 00:07:39.400
&gt;&gt; Yeah the first ten hires
are really

00:07:39.400 --> 00:07:43.950
hard because you&#39;re making
these first ten

00:07:43.950 --> 00:07:46.500
hires at a point where no
one&#39;s heard of this company,

00:07:46.500 --> 00:07:47.550
no one really wants to work
for it.

00:07:47.550 --> 00:07:48.530
You&#39;re just these,

00:07:48.530 --> 00:07:51.140
like two weird people
working on this weird idea.

00:07:51.140 --> 00:07:53.070
&gt;&gt; And like their friends
are telling them not

00:07:53.070 --> 00:07:54.190
to join.

00:07:54.190 --> 00:07:57.320
For our second employee, I
think

00:07:57.320 --> 00:07:59.800
he&#39;d accepted the offer or
he was just about to, and

00:07:59.800 --> 00:08:02.700
his best friends took him
out the night before, and it

00:08:02.700 --> 00:08:06.596
was like a full on assault
for, why you should not join

00:08:06.596 --> 00:08:09.250
this company, why this is
ruining your life basically.

00:08:10.560 --> 00:08:13.720
And so anyway the guy
subsequently

00:08:13.720 --> 00:08:14.750
continued to join.

00:08:14.750 --> 00:08:15.598
And actually one of

00:08:15.598 --> 00:08:17.771
those friends also now works
at Stripe.

00:08:17.771 --> 00:08:20.067
But this is what you&#39;re up
against.

00:08:20.067 --> 00:08:20.934
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:08:20.934 --> 00:08:24.362
And I mean it&#39;s also hard
because no batch of

00:08:24.362 --> 00:08:27.790
ten people will have as
great an influence on

00:08:27.790 --> 00:08:31.630
the company as those first
ten people.

00:08:31.630 --> 00:08:34.640
I think everyone&#39;s
impression of recruiting is,

00:08:34.640 --> 00:08:36.430
you open LinkedIn.

00:08:36.430 --> 00:08:38.050
It&#39;s sort of like ordering
off the dollar menu.

00:08:38.050 --> 00:08:40.190
It&#39;s, I want that one, that
one, and that one.

00:08:40.190 --> 00:08:42.543
And, and now you have some
hires.

00:08:42.543 --> 00:08:46.606
Whereas at least for us, it
was very much over a very

00:08:46.606 --> 00:08:50.103
long time period, talking
people we knew or

00:08:50.103 --> 00:08:53.780
friends of friends into
joining.

00:08:53.780 --> 00:08:56.880
We didn&#39;t have huge
networks, Pat and

00:08:56.880 --> 00:08:58.100
I were both in college at
the time.

00:08:58.100 --> 00:08:59.630
So there were no people that

00:08:59.630 --> 00:09:01.750
we&#39;d really worked with to
draw on, and so

00:09:01.750 --> 00:09:05.280
a lot of those early Stripes
were people we had heard of,

00:09:05.280 --> 00:09:08.990
friends of friends, and the
other interesting thing they

00:09:08.990 --> 00:09:11.665
all had in common is that
they were all

00:09:11.665 --> 00:09:16.400
early in their career, or
undervalued in some way.

00:09:16.400 --> 00:09:17.290
Cuz when you think about it,

00:09:17.290 --> 00:09:20.430
if someone is a known
spectacular quantity,

00:09:20.430 --> 00:09:22.570
then they&#39;re probably
working in a job and

00:09:22.570 --> 00:09:23.730
very happy with that.

00:09:23.730 --> 00:09:27.720
And so we have to try and
find people who were,

00:09:27.720 --> 00:09:30.860
in the case of our designer
that we hired, he was 18 and

00:09:30.860 --> 00:09:33.970
in high school and in Sweden
at the time.

00:09:33.970 --> 00:09:34.820
In the case of our,

00:09:34.820 --> 00:09:39.040
our CTO, he was in college
at the time.

00:09:39.040 --> 00:09:40.030
You know, a lot of these
people,

00:09:40.030 --> 00:09:42.820
they were early on in their
careers and

00:09:42.820 --> 00:09:46.920
the only way we could, you
can relax when constrained.

00:09:48.020 --> 00:09:49.940
You can relax the fact that
they&#39;re talented or

00:09:49.940 --> 00:09:52.212
relax that it&#39;s apparent
that they&#39;re talented,

00:09:52.212 --> 00:09:56.240
and we, not consciously, but
we relaxed the latter.

00:09:57.420 --> 00:10:03.320
&gt;&gt; Yeah, I think finding
kind of people who are, or

00:10:03.320 --> 00:10:05.130
just think like a value
investor.

00:10:05.130 --> 00:10:08.170
You&#39;re looking for the human
capital that&#39;s

00:10:09.990 --> 00:10:11.900
significantly devalued by
the market, you know?

00:10:11.900 --> 00:10:12.940
You probably shouldn&#39;t look
to

00:10:12.940 --> 00:10:15.850
hire your brilliant friends
at Facebook and Google or

00:10:15.850 --> 00:10:18.050
whatever, because they&#39;re
already discovered.

00:10:18.050 --> 00:10:19.510
You know, if they&#39;re wanting
to join that&#39;s great,

00:10:19.510 --> 00:10:21.919
but they&#39;re probably harder
to convince.

00:10:23.492 --> 00:10:25.570
John and I spent a little a
while yesterday

00:10:25.570 --> 00:10:28.790
afternoon sort of trying to
figure out in retrospect,

00:10:28.790 --> 00:10:31.490
what kind of traits our
first ten or

00:10:31.490 --> 00:10:34.320
so people had in common that
we thought were significant.

00:10:34.320 --> 00:10:37.711
And you know, in general
sort of in speaking about

00:10:37.711 --> 00:10:41.182
culture, I sort of want to
caveat everything we say

00:10:41.182 --> 00:10:45.785
with, I that sort of advice
is very limited experience,

00:10:45.785 --> 00:10:47.785
widely over extrapolated.

00:10:47.785 --> 00:10:50.690
And I think there&#39;s a lot of
truth to that.

00:10:50.690 --> 00:10:54.130
But for our particular first
ten people, the things we

00:10:54.130 --> 00:10:58.350
sort of figured out that
seemed to be important were

00:10:58.350 --> 00:11:01.760
they were also very genuine
and straight.

00:11:01.760 --> 00:11:03.900
I think that actually
matters quite a lot in that

00:11:03.900 --> 00:11:06.880
sort of they&#39;re people that
sort of that others want to

00:11:06.880 --> 00:11:10.120
work with, that they&#39;re
people that others trust.

